<div id="Idea_4114"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4114-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4114">Territorial Definition&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/5297-4049">agkaiser1</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">1 day ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Let's propose a study to determine what areas of legislation, execution and jurisdiction ought be the dominion of each level of government. The issue of the study may be a guide to legislators, administrators and courts.<br/><br/>Few would disagree that defense is the territory of the U.S. Congress and the Executive Branch in concert with one another.  Rights guaranteed by the Constitution and Amendments belong to the Federal Appeals and Supreme Courts. <br/><br/>For instance, if the issue of slavery had been left to the states, as John C. Calhoun argued via the proposition of Nullification, the South might still own slaves. [“Nullification” is the foundation for the states' rights and judicial activist rants that began to reappear in the 1950's following Brown v Board.] Obviously, state and local governments cannot be entrusted with our civil rights. Colloquial prejudice  and bigotries will preclude dealing justly with large issues that transcend state or local bounds. That's part of why we have a federal government. <br/><br/>The construction and maintenance of states' highways and bridges are left to their individual legislatures and governors. The positioning of traffic lights certainly belongs to local communities. Many other more weighty matters don't affect our common defense or universal/constitutional guarantees. They should also be the dominion of lower levels of government.<br/><br/>There's a start. What other areas might be assigned to each level of government? <br/><br/>agkaiser.org </div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_4114" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_4114', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2247&topicID=4114')">Comments (2)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_4114"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2247">Between Federal, State, and Local Governments</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_4114"></div>
</div></td>
