<div id="Idea_4051"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4051-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4051">Passport - Department of State- allow electgronic verification of birth records&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/9331-4049">flyngrl</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">1 day ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">I just applied for a passport for my son who was born in California and provided the birth certificate provided by the county he was born in.  DOS wrote back that I needed to get  "long form birth certificate" from the state.  This is a 14 week process. Why can't secure technology be used by individual states to DOS (and other agencies)? I have no problem paying the same $14.00, but in this day and age requiring a "raised seal" is silly.  I just had to get my signature notarized to get this data and the notary did not have a raised seal, explaining "this stamp is all we have."</div>
